<font color="#FF0000">FLAG DESECRATION AMENDMENT</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 13 11:04:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
     On June 9, the US House of Representatives will vote on an amendment to the Constitution that, if adopted, will ban flag desecration.  In 1995, this same amendment passed the House and failed only by a few votes in the US Senate.  As a result of the elections in 1996 which increased representation by political conservatives,  the Senate is poised to approve this amendment and send it to the States.  In 1995,  well over 3/4 of the State legislatures passed resolutions indicating that they would ratify an the flag desecration amendment under consideration at that time.  Now, two years later, it seems almost certain that this amendment will be ratified and adopted.<br><br>
     I am a VietNam era veteran.  I volunteered for service in the Army in 1966 because I believed in free speech.  Of the many crimes committed by Communists in the Soviet/Chinese bloc, one of the worst was the systematic persecution of citizens who spoke out in opposition to the Party and its policies.  I believed then, and still believe that any ideology that violates this inalienable and very basic human right in this way is totalitarian and therefore despicable.  Where freedom of speech is restricted, slavery takes root and flourishes.  <br><br>
     I thought, in 1966, that most Americans agreed with me, and that we were fighting Communism in order to at least contain, if not defeat, this pernicious threat to our freedom.  Now I find that most Americans are quite eager to deify a piece of cloth and persecute those who would use it to criticize the government that it represents. <br><br>
    I am angry, disgusted and not about to remain silent.  A bought-out bunch of sanctimonious ex-draft dodgers (eg. Phil Gramm, Trent Lott, Dick Armey, Newt Gingrich, and many others in both whorehouses of Congress) is about to take one small step towards returning to the days when the Constitution recognized and protected legalized slavery.<br><br>
   In 1995, I more or less founded a vet's organization devoted to protecting the Constitution from desecration by flag-happy far right.  It is called &quot;Vets For Free Speech.&quot;  It has no hierarchy, dues, or membership rolls. Any vet who, like me, loves freedom and will not worship a piece of cloth is a member if he wants to be.  The important thing is to speak out and act up to demonstrate your commitment to free speech, while it  is still legal to do so.  <br><br>
    On July 4, 1995, soon after the last flag desecration amendment passed the Whorehouse of Representatives, there was a parade here in Rockford, Illinois.  Parade organizers told a local newspaper that all veterans were invited to march in the parade.  When I showed up carrying signs identifying my organization and explaining our opposition to the amendment, I was banned from marching in the parade, threatened with arrest if I tried to do so, and threatened and insulted repeatedly by parade participants and spectators as I walked along the sidewalks beside the parade route, but that did not bother me.  For the first time in my life, I felt that I was really defending, peaceably and intelligently, for myself and future generation, what I was told was being defended, violently and immorally, by the war effort in Vietnam.  It felt really good.<br><br>
    I urge other vets to join me this year in a nationwide protest against this amendment and all that it represents.  Your comments, pro and con, publicly to this website and privately to my email address, are welcome.  Together, and perhaps for the first time in our lives, we can really defend freedom and feel justifiably proud of having done so.<br><br>
       John M. Stassi<br>
       Vets For Free Speech<br>
       &quot;Old Glory:  If a vet can't burn it, then it wasn't worth                            fighting for.&quot;<br><br>

